SIMPLE: paternity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Paternity
<hw>Pa*ter"ni*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>paternitas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>paternit⟦eacute⟧</ets>. See
<er>Paternal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The relation of a father to
his child; fathership; fatherhood; family headship; <as>as, the divine
<ex>paternity</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The world, while it had scarcity of people, underwent no other
dominion than <qex>paternity</qex> and eldership.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Derivation or descent from a father; male parentage;
<as>as, the <ex>paternity</ex> of a child</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Origin; authorship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>paternity</qex> of these novels was . . . disputed.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Paternoster</ent>⟦br⟧
